Exports Drive Day-Ahead Czech Power Prices Higher, Poland Drops

-- B y   M a r e k   S t r z e l e c k i
-- 
2011-05-24T14:28:31Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-24/exports-drive-day-ahead-czech-power-prices-higher-poland-drops.html
Cross-border electricity flows
boosted Czech day-ahead prices and sent Polish deliveries lower.  Czech day-ahead power advanced 1.9 percent to 61.67 euros
($87) a megawatt-hour as the equivalent contract in  Germany , a
benchmark for eastern Europe, gained 2.1 percent to 61.75 euros
a megawatt-hour, according to broker data compiled by Bloomberg.  Polish electricity for tomorrow fell 1.6 percent to 212.23
zloty ($76.85) a megawatt-hour, according to Polish power
exchange data compiled by Bloomberg.  Hungarian electricity, traded on the Budapest-based power
exchange, rose 0.2 percent to 60.91 euros, according to the
bourse’s website.  The  Czech Republic  has 17,625 megawatts of capacity
installed, according to Bloomberg data. The country was a net
exporter of power at 2:50 p.m. local time, with net cross border
outflow of 2,545 megawatts according to CEPS, the Czech power
transmission system operator.  Poland ’s exports were balanced by
imports between 1 p.m. and 2 p.m., compared with 433 megawatts
exported at the same time yesterday, according to  Entsoe , the
European Transmission System Operators transparency platform.  Bloomberg tracks power prices from brokers including GFI
Group Inc., ICAP Plc, Spectron Group Ltd., Tradition Financial
Services and Tullett Prebon Plc. Brokers handle the majority of
trading in  Europe ’s electricity markets.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Marek Strzelecki in Warsaw at 
